commit.message:
Make version 1 of the snippet parser the default

It's been 3 years. It's time.

Closes #278.
Update README
Add clarifying statement

Add SnipLookupPre and SnipLookupPost User autocmds

These run before/after SnipMate determines its own lookups. If Pre finds
lookups, the normal SnipMate ones are not loaded. Post can be used to
add lookups to the normal set.

This is the first User-facing autocommand, and probably won't be the
last. There will likely need to be some tweaking to how they work.

Fix mistakes in install instructions

These were pointed out by h3xx.

Add zero tabstop before building location objects

Before, it was added after most location objects were built. This could
lead to a situation where a stop earlier on the line that the $0 is
also on could change without the zero stop updating accordingly.

This could be avoided by specifying the $0. Or by just fixing this bug.

Make tlib an optional dependency

There were two locations where tlib was actually used.
- One was for showing snippets with OpenSnippetFiles, a command that's
  likely to be removed at some point.
- One was for picking multisnip snippets, where inputlist() suffices
  just fine.
The second case will probably have a third option eventually: tlib,
inputlist(), and using the pop up menu the way ShowAvailableSnips()
does.

In both cases, it's an unnecessary requirement. It'll likely be
completely removed from SnipMate, but some other things have to come
first.

Most of this work came from the tlib_fix branch.
Release version 0.90

Update installation instructions

This leaves Vim's native package manager as the default, while still
allowing for alternate package managers.

Fixes #297.

Fix jumps when &sel == 'exclusive'

Should fix #285.

Document the _ scope

See #288.
Fix doc formatting

Remove newline at the end of a VISUAL expansion

Earlier state was still having this issue.
Added check as substring match with for that last list entry for being
leading space till end.
Tested for different cases, desired behaviour observed.
improve documentation, add always_choose_first

Fix bugs with completion and non-standard bindings

If the completion menu is visible and the user triggers a snippet
command, the completion menu is normally dismissed so that the snippet
command can execute. In order to do this, SnipMate uses `feedkeys` to
dismiss the menu, then also uses `feedkeys` so that the snippet function
gets called again after the menu is dismissed.

However, in the current SnipMate code, this second part is accomplished
via a call to `feedkeys("\<tab>")`, which only works if we're using the
default SnipMate bindings. If a non-standard binding is used, then the
snippet fails to trigger.

(This is perhaps less of an issue when the user has more direct control
over the completion menu, but it renders SnipMate unusable when it's
combined with a plugin like YouCompleteMe where the completion menu
appears automatically as you type.)

This change also fixes a possible issue where `feedkeys("\<tab>")` might
have triggered `snipMateNextOrTrigger` even if the original command the
user had executed might have been `snipMateTrigger`.

Improve parser version documentation

See #248.

Check 'rtp' when needed instead of onload

Before this commit, SnipMate would check 'rtp' only when it's loaded.
Any changes to 'rtp', say at runtime, would not affect SnipMate's
snippet searching procedures.
